This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it describes a framework for defining high-order image models that can be used in a variety of applications, including contour detection and binary segmentation. The paper also discusses modeling local patterns in a multiscale representation of an image, which is a common technique in computer vision. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it uses an MCMC method for block sampling with very large blocks for inference and learning. 

The artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper discusses the use of expressive priors that depend on a relatively small number of parameters, which is a common approach in AI. 

The graphics (cs.GR) sub-category is a possibility as the paper discusses contour detection, which is a common problem in computer graphics. 

Finally, the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category is a possibility as the paper discusses binary segmentation, which is a common problem in multimedia applications such as video processing.
